class Student {
    int id;
    String name;
}

public class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Student s1 = new Student(); // s1 is a reference to a Student object
        s1.id = 101;
        s1.name = "John";

        Student s2 = s1;  // s2 is another reference to the same object

        s2.name = "David";

        System.out.println(s1.name);  // Output: David
    }
}



s1 refers to a Student object.

s2 = s1; means both s1 and s2 refer to the same object in memory.

Changing s2.name also affects s1.name because they are pointing to the same object.


Reference vs Primitive Types
Feature	   Primitive Type	     Reference Type
Stored in	Stack	Stack       (reference), Heap (actual object)
Contains	Actual value	       Address of the object
Examples	int, char, float	String, Array, Class objects
Copied by	Value	               Reference


Student s = null;
System.out.println(s.name);

